Kim Yong Nam meets Libyan guests 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, President of the presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, today met and had a talk with Abdulrahman Mohamed Shalgham, secretary of the general people's committee for foreign liaison and international cooperation of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya, and his party at the Mansudae Assembly Hall. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Present there were Kim Yong Il, vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs, and other officials concerned, Ahmed Amer al Muakkaf, secretary of the people's bureau of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya in the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Abdulrahman Mohamed Shalgham said at the meeting that the friendship between the two countries forged by Moammer El Gaddafi and Kim Il Sung has a long history. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The close cooperation between the two countries proved that nothing can break the friendly relations between them, he said, adding Libya hopes these ties will further expand and develop.

Greetings to governor-general of commonwealth of Bahamas 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, President of the presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, sent a message of greetings on July 8 to Orville Alton Turnquest, governor-general of the commonwealth of Bahamas, on the occasion of the 27th anniversary of its independence. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The message congratulated the governor-general and people of Bahamas on the 27th anniversary of the independence of Bahamas and wished him success in his work for the prosperity and progress of the country.

Hong Song Nam meets Libyan secretary and his party 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Hong Song Nam, premier of the DPRK cabinet, today met and conversed with Abdulrahman Mohamed Shalgham, secretary of the general people's committee for foreign liaison and international cooperation of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya, and his party at the Mansudae Assembly Hall. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Present there were Kang Jong Mo, Minister of Foreign Trade, Kim Yong Il, vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs, officials concerned and  Ahmed Amer al Muakkaf, secretary of the people's bureau of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya in the DPRK.

Gift to Kim Jong Il 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- General Secretary Kim Jong Il received a gift from the secretary of the general people's committee for foreign liaison and international cooperation of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The gift was handed to Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun by secretary Abdulrahman Mohamed Shalgham on a visit to the DPRK.

Wreaths laid before Kim Hyong Jik's statue and grave 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Senior party and state, officials, working people and school youth and children today laid wreaths before the statue of Kim Hyong Jik, an indomitable revolutionary fighter and outstanding leader of the anti-Japanese national liberation movement in Korea, in Ponghwa-ri, Kangdong county, on the outskirts of Pyongyang and before his grave in Mangyongdae  on the occasion of his 106th birth anniversary. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Wreaths sent by General Secretary Kim Jong Il were laid there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Senior party and state officials including Kye Ung Thae, Kim Chol Man, Choe Thae Bok, Yang Hyong Sop and Choe Yong Rim were present there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Wreaths and bouquets were placed before his statue and grave in the name of the Central Committee of the Worker's Party of Korea,  the presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, the DPRK cabinet, ministries, national institutions, working people's organizations and educational organs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Wreaths were also laid before his statues in Sakju county, North Phyongan Province and Junggang county, Jagang Province.

Letter to Kim Jong Il 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- General Secretary Kim Jong Il received a letter from Choe Hong Hui, president of the International Taekwon-do Federation, on Saturday on the occasion of the 6th anniversary of the passing away of the President Kim Il Sung. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   President Kim Il Sung was a peerlessly great man whom the Korean people acclaimed for the first time in the history of thousands of years and a great benefactor of him and 50 million orthodox Taekwon-do players, the letter said.  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Kim Jong Il, who is identical with the President, is a tender-hearted father of the Korean nation and the sun and lodestar of national reunification, the letter noted. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The north-south summit was held for the first time 55 years after the division of the country and the north-south joint declaration made public, which is the great result of his broad-minded magnanimity, his firm will to reunify the country in our era and his idea of the national reunification, said the letter. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The letter expressed the determination to work hard to put into practice the pledge made before Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Il to make contributions to national reunification through Taekwon-do.

Months of maritime sports begin 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- July and August are months of maritime sports in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Meetings for opening maritime sports months were held in Pyongyang, provinces, cities and counties (districts) on July 2 and 9. Swimming and wading pools have been wonderfully built everywhere in the country. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   At the meetings it was stressed that all school youth and children should firmly prepare themselves for labour and the national defence to be more diligent in studies and loyal to their organizations and thus grow into the reliable successors to the revolutionary cause of Juche. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The meetings were followed by swimming matches.

Reception in honor of Libyan guests 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- The government of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea yesterday gave a reception in honor of the secretary of the general people's committee for foreign liaison and international cooperation of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya and his party at the Mansudae Assembly Hall. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Foreign Minister Paek Nam Sun in his speech said that the friendship between the DPRK and Libya based on the particular intimacy between the President Kim Il Sung and Colonel Moammer El Gaddafi, leader of the great September 1st Revolution, is invariably and favourably developing even under the complicated international situation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Noting that the Korean people are sincerely rejoiced over the successes made by the government and people of Libya in their work to build a free and prosperous Libya, he extended support and solidarity with the struggle of the Libyan people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Korean people will strive to strengthen and develop the friendly and cooperative relations with Libya in accordance with the good experience and traditions established in the anti-imperialist struggle, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Secretary Abdulrahman Mohamed Shalgham said in his speech that although the U.S. is holding back the normal development of the two countries, the two peoples will surely realize the common cause. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    He continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    Libya will develop the existing bilateral relations between the two countries on the basis of the relations provided by Colonel Moammer El Gaddafi and the eternal President Kim Il Sung. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    The friendly relations between Libya and the DPRK will continue developing amid the concern of the leader of the Korean people Kim Jong Il, who is carrying forward the cause of the eternal President Kim Il Sung.

Talks between DPRK and Libyan foreign ministers 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Talks between Paek Nam Sun, Foreign Minister of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, and Abdulrahman Mohamed Shalgham, secretary of the general people's committee for foreign liaison and international cooperation of the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya, were held at the Mansudae Assembly Hall in Pyongyang yesterday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   At the talks both sides informed each other of political situation of their countries and exchanged views on the development of relations between the two countries and a series of matters of mutual concern. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Present at the talks were DPRK officials concerned, the Libyan secretary's party and Ahmed Amer al Muakkaf, secretary of the people's bureau of the Geat Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya to Korea.

Ideological and theoretical exploits of Kim Il Sung 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Works of the President Kim Il Sung are being published in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The publication of "Kim Il Sung's Works" containing his major works was completed with 50 volumes in April Juche 86 (1997). &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   "Complete collection of Kim Il Sung's Works" containing all his works compiled in chronological order has been published since April Juche 81 (1992). Supplemented with his works into which new researches have been made, the collection has 31 volumes at present. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He published more than 3,070 major works in the whole period of his revolutionary activities. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He conducted his ideological and theoretical activities in revolutionary practice, not in study. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He made public nearly 60 works including his first work "Down with Imperialism" in days of the anti-Japanese revolution, providing the guidelines precious in speeding up the victory of the anti-Japanese national liberation struggle. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He published over 320 works during the period of the Fatherland Liberation War (June 1950-July 1953), thus arousing the army and people to victory. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He made public nearly 2,700 works to give perfect answers to all theoretical and practical questions in carrying on the Korean revolution and human cause of independence during the period of building a new democratic Korea, post-war reconstruction and socialist construction of different stages.

Kim Hyong Jik, indomitable revolutionary fighter 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Today marks the 106th birth anniversary of an indomitable revolutionary fighter Kim Hyong Jik. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He embarked upon the road of revolution with the spirit of "aim high" in his early years and devotedly struggled for the liberation of the country and the happiness of people to the last moments of his life. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Kim Hyong Jik was the outstanding leader of the Korean national liberation movement and the great pioneer in changing the course of the struggle from the nationalist movement to the communist movement. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He inaugurated the Korean National Association on March 23, 1917, at Hakdanggol, Pyongyang, to develop the national liberation movement to a higher stage. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   This association was an anti-Japanese underground revolutionary organization which was transparent in anti-imperialist stand and national independent stand and biggest in its scale and activity scope in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   After its inauguration, he developed the national liberation movement in Korea to a new stage of development by putting forward the idea that people should have the spirit of national independence, enlarging as well as expand strengthen organisation and a policy that they should wipe out the armed enemy with arms and performing the immortal exploits in the struggle for this. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Indeed, his life was the brilliant one of an ardent patriot who devoted his all to the independence of the country and the prosperity of all generations to come. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Therefore, his revolutionary exploits will shine for all ages. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   His statues are standing in Kangdong county, Pyongyang, Sakju county, North Phyongan Province, Junggang county, Jagang Province, and other places associated with his immortal revolutionary exploits. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   And his revolutionary museums and monuments were built in different places and his relics are preserved. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Several units and schools have been named after him. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Among them are Kim Hyong Jik University of Education, Kim Hyong Jik People's Hospital and Kim Hyong Jik county. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Feature films, including "The Green Pine Tree," "Dawn" and "The Untrodden Path," showing his revolutionary life and struggle were created.

Japan's anti-DPRK charade 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- The Japanese government reportedly decided to mention "missile threat from North Korea" in a special statement to be adopted at the Okinawa summit of major nations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Japanese authorities seek a despicable and wicked aim in floating again the fiction of "missile threat," a product of their hostile policy towards the DPRK, in a bid to build up public opinion through an international fora. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Japan is a thrice-cursed criminal state which imposed immeasurable disasters, misfortune and sufferings upon the Korean people while enforcing an unprecedented military rule during its occupation of Korea in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Though more than half a century has passed since then, Japan has neither made any apology or compensation to the Korean people nor honestly reflected on its past crimes. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Japan, far from drawing a proper lesson from its history of bloody war, is stepping up arms buildup after throwing off the mask of "pacifist state" in a bid to realize its old dream of "Greater East Asia Coprosperity Sphere." It is also busy with the retrogressive revision of the constitution for its overseas aggression. Japan cites "missile threat from North Korea" as a justification for these moves. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Japanese authorities' ulterior aim to bring "missile threat" from the DPRK to the Okinawa summit of major nations for discussion is to tarnish the international authority and image of the DPRK, mislead the world public opinion urging Japan to honestly reflect on its past crimes and justify its moves to become a military power. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   This sinister and wicked intention of Japan is intolerable as it is an unbearable insult and mockery of the Korean people and the international community. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   If Japan truly wishes to fulfil its obligation and responsibility as a member of the international community it should clearly redeem its crimes committed against the Korean people and humankind in the past, instead of trying to achieve its sinister aim by wooing others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Japan is well-advised to face up to the trend of the times and drop its anachronistic anti-DPRK hostile policy.

Arboretum carries people's best wishes 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- There is a wonderful arboretum near the Kumsusan Memorial Palace in Pyongyang. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   At least 500,000 trees and flower plants of some 260 species are growing in the arboretum covering 100 hectares. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Among them are 11,700 flower trees of 54 species. Plants of various species including woody plants are harmoniously distributed in well-systematized plant zones. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   This arboretum bears witness to the best wishes of the Korean people and the world revolutionary people for the eternal life of the President Kim Il Sung. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Flowers loved by him in his lifetime and rare trees found in the places where he visited have been transplanted there by the sincere efforts of people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   A zelkova tree weighing over 10 tons was transplanted by officials of a national institution and a family from Kangdong county, Pyongyang, transplanted with all sincerity over 1,000 magnolia trees there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Pupils of senior middle schools across the country make nests and send them to the arboretum every year to let birds of various species fly in the area. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    In the arboretum there are lots of rare plants sent by many figures of China, Russia, Mongolia and other countries including the chairman of the Danish Dendrologists Association. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
    It also received 200 Siberian rowan trees sent by the people in the village of internationalist soldier Ya. T. Novichenko. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Overseas compatriots made sincere contributions to the arboretum. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   A Korean style park will appear in the center of the arboretum before long. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Thanks to these devoted efforts of the Korean people and the world progressive people the arboretum will not only add to the scenic beauty of the sacred temple of Juche but serve as a wonderful center for scientific research and a cultural recreation ground for people.

Kim Il Sung's external activities brilliantly recorded in world political history 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- On the occasion of the sixth anniversary of the passing away of the President Kim Il Sung (July 8, 1994) the Korean people and the world progressives look back with deep emotion on the exploits the President performed through his energetic external activities in the idea of independence, peace and friendship, the feats brilliantly recorded in the world political history. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   In the whole period when the President was active as head of the Worker's Party of Korea and the state, he met with at least 70,000 figures of 136 foreign countries irrespective of their ideologies and ideal, political views and religious beliefs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Among them were more than 230 heads of state and government including Stalin, Mao Zedong, Sukarno, Tito, Ho Chi Minh, Mitterrand and Houari Boumedienne. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   In June Juche 83 (1994) alone, the last year of his life, the President energetically worked, meeting former U.S. President Jimmy Carter and other foreign delegations and personages on some 20 occasions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He spent several hours, discussing with Carter important issues of bringing about a radical turn in the efforts for peace and security on the Korean peninsula and the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He also participated in the 85th inter-parliamentary conference and other international meetings where he made speeches such as "for a free and peaceful new world" and "preventing war and preserving peace are the burning tasks of mankind" to elucidate principled problems in accomplishing the human cause of independence. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Answering the questions raised by the Washington Times, the Japanese politico-theoretical magazine Sekai, the French newspaper Le Monde and many other foreign media, the President gave scientific answers to the problems arising in building a new independent world free from war and aggression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The President covered over 522,440 km to visit the former Soviet Union, China, Indonesia, Yugoslavia, Vietnam, Algeria and other countries and thus left ineffaceable marks to shine long in history.

Three-point charter of Korea's reunification supported abroad 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 10 (KCNA) -- Tajik and Guyanese organizations took part in the international signature campaign to support the three-point charter of Korea's reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   All the members of the Tajik February 16 Association for the Study of the Juche Idea named after "general Kim Jong Il" signed the signature paper on July 3. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Meanwhile, Hitraka Dass, coordinator of the Guyanese Women's Organization for People's Progress, signed the paper on behalf of its 12,000 members on June 28.
